{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3cc916b2-bd04-499a-a7e7-98173465938b","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC from stdin and write responses to stdout (libraries like `ModelContextProtocol` or `McpDotNet` handle this).\n- **Don't** write logs to stdout — use stderr instead, or they'll corrupt the protocol.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the executable.\n\nFor a **published** build (faster startup):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"737504be-1406-46f9-8fed-f01a11ce3e7e","outputTokens":338,"requestId":"F3D4:184190:10F051:1527D5:69F54DE7"},"id":"9096707a-340c-4673-9453-9ee9fe324183","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:05:51.587Z","parentId":"555caa09-eadb-4ffd-a4d7-58f868b6b2e8"}
